    body: "Sitting in the courtyard of a Marrakech riad during the city's annual film festival, Cate Blanchett looks entirely at ease. The actress, who turns 57 this year, is in a reflective mood as she discusses a career that has spanned Shakespeare, superheroes, and everything in between.\n\n\"I think the greatest gift of aging as an actor is that you stop caring about perception,\" Blanchett says, sipping mint tea. \"When I was younger, I was always thinking about how a role would be received. Now I just think: does this excite me? Does it terrify me? If the answer to both is yes, I'm in.\"\n\nHer latest project, Terrence Malick's \"The Horizon,\" reportedly required her to spend three months living in a remote village in Patagonia with no script and only minimal direction. \"Terry would just say, 'Live here. Observe. The film will find you.' It was the most challenging and liberating experience of my professional life.\"\n\nBeyond acting, Blanchett has recently taken on the role of UN Goodwill Ambassador for Climate Action, a cause she describes as \"the defining challenge of our time.\" She's been instrumental in pushing for sustainable practices in film production, persuading several major studios to adopt carbon-neutral filming protocols.\n\n\"Artists have always been at the forefront of social change,\" she argues. \"We have platforms and resources that many activists don't. If we don't use them responsibly, what's the point of having them? The film industry has a massive carbon footprint. It's time we took that seriously.\"",
