    body: "In a result that has stunned industry analysts, A24's \"Moth\" — a psychological horror film made for just $4.5 million — opened to an astonishing $95 million at the domestic box office this weekend. The film, directed by 28-year-old Mexican filmmaker Mariana Ochoa, is now the highest-grossing debut for a first-time director in cinema history.\n\n\"Moth\" tells the story of a rural Mexican village where residents begin to experience shared nightmares that manifest in waking life. The film eschews jump scares in favor of a slow-building atmosphere of dread that has drawn comparisons to the work of Robert Eggers and Ari Aster, though Ochoa's approach is distinctly her own.\n\nThe film's success is largely attributed to word-of-mouth and social media. Clips and theories about the film's ambiguous ending have generated billions of views on TikTok, with fans dissecting every frame for hidden meanings. \"Moth\" has achieved something rare in modern cinema — it has become a communal experience that people feel compelled to discuss and revisit.\n\nA24 has expanded the film's theatrical run from 800 to 3,200 screens in response to overwhelming demand. Internationally, the film opened to $68 million, bringing its global total to $163 million in just ten days. Ochoa, who grew up in Oaxaca and studied film on a scholarship at NYU, has become an overnight sensation.\n\n\"I made this film with my friends in the village where I grew up,\" Ochoa said in a statement. \"The fact that people around the world are connecting with this story about fear, community, and the things we can't explain — it's beyond anything I dared to dream.\"",
