    body: "The Walt Disney Company has announced the acquisition of Legendary Entertainment in a deal valued at approximately $12 billion, marking the largest entertainment merger since Disney's purchase of 21st Century Fox. The deal gives Disney control of Legendary's extensive IP library and its lucrative partnerships with Warner Bros. and Universal.\n\nLegendary's portfolio includes the MonsterVerse franchise, the Dune series, and properties like Pacific Rim and The Dark Knight trilogy. The acquisition also brings Legendary East, the company's Chinese joint venture, under Disney's umbrella, significantly strengthening the conglomerate's position in the world's second-largest film market.\n\nDisney CEO Bob Iger described the acquisition as \"a natural evolution of our content strategy. Legendary has built an incredible library of globally recognized IP that perfectly complements our existing franchises. We see enormous opportunities for theme parks, streaming content, and consumer products.\"\n\nThe deal faced immediate scrutiny from antitrust regulators, with the FTC announcing a 90-day review period. Media watchdog organizations expressed concern about further consolidation in an industry already dominated by a handful of conglomerates. \"This deal gives Disney an even more dangerous level of control over what stories get told,\" said one industry analyst.\n\nFor Legendary's leadership, the deal represents a lucrative exit after years of navigating complex distribution partnerships. CEO Josh Grode will remain in a leadership role overseeing the Legendary division within Disney, and the company's Burbank headquarters will be maintained as a distinct production hub.",
