    body: "The 98th Academy Awards ceremony at the Dolby Theatre was a night of historic firsts and deeply emotional tributes that reminded the world why the Oscars remain the pinnacle of cinematic celebration. From the opening monologue to the final envelope, the evening was charged with significance.\n\nThe night's biggest story was Lily Gladstone's win for Best Actress, making her the first Native American woman to win the award. Her acceptance speech, delivered partly in the Blackfoot language, drew a standing ovation. \"This belongs to every little girl on every reservation who was told her stories didn't matter,\" Gladstone said, her voice breaking. \"Your stories matter. You matter.\"\n\nBest Picture went to \"The Weight of Salt,\" Pedro Pascal's critically acclaimed drama about the Chilean immigrant experience. Director Alejandro González Iñárritu used his acceptance speech to advocate for immigrant communities facing increasing hostility. \"Cinema is empathy,\" he said. \"In a world that wants to build walls, we build bridges.\"\n\nA particularly moving In Memoriam segment honored the late Sidney Poitier, Angela Lansbury, and Robbie Robertson, with a performance by Jon Batiste that had the entire theater visibly emotional. The segment concluded with a montage of Poitier's most iconic roles, ending on his famous line from \"In the Heat of the Night.\"\n\nThe ceremony's host, Quinta Brunson, earned widespread praise for her warmth and wit, balancing humor with genuine emotion. Her opening number, a musical tribute to the year's most memorable films, set the tone for an evening that felt both celebratory and deeply human.",
