    title: "Squid Game Season 3 Breaks Netflix Viewership Records in Every Territory",
    excerpt: "The final season of Hwang Dong-huk's global phenomenon draws 320 million households in its first week, cementing the series as Netflix's crown jewel.",
    body: "Netflix has confirmed that Squid Game Season 3 has shattered every viewership record in the platform's history, drawing an estimated 320 million households in its first seven days of release. The Korean survival drama's final chapter has proven to be a global cultural event of unprecedented scale.\n\nCreator Hwang Dong-huk returns to direct all seven episodes, which he has described as \"the conclusion the characters deserve.\" The final season introduces a new game structure where past winners are forced to compete against each other, raising the stakes to existential heights.\n\n\"I never imagined when I wrote the first season that it would become what it has,\" Hwang told CelebPost through a translator. \"The pressure was immense. But I realized that the pressure the characters feel is the same pressure I feel as a storyteller. That became the theme — the cost of winning.\"\n\nThe series has been particularly dominant in markets where Netflix has historically struggled, including India, Brazil, and the Middle East. In South Korea, the finale reportedly caused a national moment of collective viewing, with streets emptying as audiences tuned in simultaneously. The government declared it a cultural achievement.\n\nNetflix co-CEO Ted Sarandos called the series \"the most important original content in our company's history.\" The streaming giant has already greenlit multiple spin-off projects, including an American-set companion series and an animated prequel, though Hwang himself has indicated he will step away from the franchise to pursue original work.",
    author: "Robert Pham",
    date: "2026-04-18",
    readTime: "9 min",
