    id: 49,
    cat: "INTERVIEW",
    title: "Lupita Nyong'o on Art, Activism, and Finding Peace in an Uncertain World",
    excerpt: "The Oscar winner discusses her new documentary about wildlife conservation in Kenya, her approach to choosing roles, and why she's never felt more centered.",
    body: "Lupita Nyong'o sits cross-legged on a low sofa in a sunlit room at the Sundance Film Festival, radiating a calm that feels almost gravitational. The actress is here to premiere \"Serengeti Rising,\" a documentary she directed and produced about the intersection of wildlife conservation and community development in her native Kenya.\n\n\"This project has been my heart for three years,\" Nyong'o says, her eyes brightening. \"We followed a group of Maasai women who are pioneering a new model of conservation — one that centers indigenous knowledge and community benefit rather than the old colonial model of fences and exclusion. These women are saving elephants and educating children simultaneously.\"\n\nThe documentary has already drawn comparisons to the work of Jane Goodall and David Attenborough, though Nyong'o's approach is distinctly personal. She narrates the film herself, weaving her own family's history in Kenya with the broader story of conservation on the continent. \"My grandmother used to tell me stories about living alongside wildlife. Those stories are disappearing. This film is my way of preserving them.\"\n\nAs an actress, Nyong'o has become increasingly selective about her projects. She turned down multiple franchise offers in favor of working with auteurs like Denis Villeneuve and Steve McQueen. \"I'd rather do one film that matters than five films that entertain,\" she says. \"There's nothing wrong with entertainment, but I only have so much time. I want to spend it on stories that stay with people.\"\n\nHer personal life, she says, has found a peaceful rhythm. She splits her time between Nairobi, New York, and a recently purchased home in Lisbon. \"I used to feel guilty about resting,\" she admits. \"Now I understand that rest isn't laziness. It's preparation. The world needs our best energy, and you can't give that if you're running on empty.\"",
